    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nIn my code, I am wrapping a Python object inside a struct to perform I/O through function pointers. The struct is then passed to a C function defined in an external C library. This function returns 0 on success, or a positive integer (corresponding to return code defined in the library) on errors. If the I/O on the Python object fails, an exception is recorded but then an error code is returned in the C function.\n\nCurrently, the ways to check for exceptions are the following:\n- `noexcept`, for functions that do not raise exceptions (not the case here)\n- `except SOME_VALUE` when a specific value is always used to signal an exception (not the case here)\n- `except *` to always check for exceptions (_de facto_ what we need here, even though on success it should be skipped).\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nI would like to do:\n```cython\ncdef extern int some_function(...) except? not 0:\n    ...\n```\nso that the exception check happens on any return value that is *not* zero (or any value for that matter). This way, exception check is always skipped on success, unlike with `except *`; and because different return codes may be returned, `except SOME_VALUE` cannot be used.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\nCurrently the alternative is to use `except *`, which unfortunately makes an exception check even on function success.\n\n### Additional context\n\nI feel this wouldn't be hard to implement given it's just negating the condition used normally for `except? SOME_VALUE`.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "If you want a short-term workaround it's relatively easy to define wrapper macros. Something like: \n\n```\ncdef extern from \"filename.h\":\n    \"\"\"\n    define wrap_function(x, y, z) (function(x, y, z) != 0)\n    \"\"\"\n    int wrap_function(int x, int y, int z) except 1\n    # or\n    int function \"wrap_function\"(int x, int y, int z) except 1\n```\n\nPersonally, I haven't missed this exact use-case but I've occasionally missed other exception checks that don't quite work with `==` like `isnan`. So I could see why this might be useful.",
